Thank you, [~mbacchi] and [~tsugawa] for specific and very helpful feedback. Check to ensure I got it all - will appear in 10 AM doc build. 

[~tsugawa] in that bulleted list, is it possible to be more specific than "step 6" ... I'm not even sure what step 6 it is referring to.
{quote}
If you only have one interface on your host then you need to follow the instructions from Midokura on setting up a veth pair so that MidoNet can take over a virtual interface rather than a physical one, as in this example (skip step 6 for Eucalyptus installs): 
{quote}

[~kmeredith] here are the missing items, the 3 numbered items are in {color:red}RED{color} while the steps in those items are standard black(sigh, formatting in confluence is poor...)

{color:red}1.{color} (TODO Item I hadn't yet gotten to from 7/14) In the section "Install Midolman on Eucalyptus components", add a new step 6:

Configure Midolman resource usage template with one of the following template names (depending on the size of your installation):

{code:java}
agent-compute-large
agent-compute-medium
agent-gateway-large
agent-gateway-medium
default
{code}

To set this resource template, run the command(replace TEMPLATE_NAME with your preferred template):
{code:java}
mn-conf template-set -h local -t TEMPLATE_NAME
{code}

Note: This is documented on the Midokura site here: http://docs.midokura.com/docs/v1.9/en/quick-start-guide/rhel-7_juno-osp/content/_midolman_installation.html

Note: For standard (small or medium) Eucalyptus clouds use the default template.  For large gateway nodes, use the _agent-gateway-large_ template, and for large Eucalyptus clouds use the _agent-compute-large_ template.


{color:red}2. {color}For the Tomcat AJP (port 8009) comment Mauricio mentioned, under the section "Install the MidoNet API on the Cloud Controller (CLC)", step 7 should now contain substeps 7.a, and we will add a new substep 7.b, it will look like this now:

7. Modify /etc/tomcat/server.xml

a. Only allow localhost access to the API. (the rest of step 7.a is what step 7 was prior.)
b. Comment out the Connector Port 8009 (AJP) line:
It should now look like:

{code:java}
<!-- Connector port="8009" protocol="AJP/1.3" redirectPort="8443" -->
{code}


{color:red}3. {color}For the Midonet logging steps that Mauricio mentioned, add an OPTIONAL step 8 (must go before current step 8 Start Tomcat):
8. Optional: Change Tomcat logging properties to reduce excessive logging and avoid filling up the /var/log filesystem.
a. Disable ConsoleHandler (described in https://tomcat.apache.org/tomcat-7.0-doc/logging.html - "Considerations for productive usage")

Edit /etc/tomcat/logging.properties and replace the line:
{code:java}
.handlers = 1catalina.org.apache.juli.FileHandler, java.util.logging.ConsoleHandler
{code}

with:

{code:java}
.handlers = 1catalina.org.apache.juli.FileHandler
{code}

b. Set log level to WARN to avoid unnecessary jersey logs.  In the file /etc/tomcat/logging.properties:

Replace the line: 

{code:java}
1catalina.org.apache.juli.FileHandler.level = FINE
{code}

with:

{code:java}
1catalina.org.apache.juli.FileHandler.level = WARN
{code}

c. Disable midonet-api writing to STDOUT.  Comment out the following lines in /usr/share/midonet-api/WEB-INF/classes/logback.xml (this example shows the comment characters already added):

{code:java}
<!--
<appender name="STDOUT" class="ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender">
<encoder>
<pattern>%d
{yyyy.MM.dd HH:mm:ss.SSS}

%-5level %logger
{0}

- %m%n%rEx </pattern>
</encoder>
</appender>
-->
{code}
